“ But,’' it is objected, “ if the House votes separ- ately on the motions for death and for banishment, the motion for acquittal will get a majority.'' But what is that to the parties who vote? Certainly it ill becomes them t'o fight tooth and nail to defeat the milder verdict. “Still,'' they say, “those who would condemn the accused either capitally or to banish- ment, should be first matched against those who would acquit them, and afterwards against each other.” Thus as in certain public gemes one competitor is 'reserved and set apart by lot to engage with the conqueror of the rest; so, it seems, in the Senate there is a first and s'econd combnt, and of two motione, the prevailing one has still a third to contend with.
